<sect2 id="script-fu-lava">
  <title>Lava</title>

  <indexterm>
    <primary>Filters</primary>
    <secondary>Render</secondary>
    <tertiary>Lava</tertiary>
  </indexterm>
  <indexterm><primary>Lava</primary></indexterm>

  <sect3>
    <title>Overview</title>

    <figure>
      <title>Example for the <quote>Lava</quote> filter</title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="JPG"
            fileref="images/filters/examples/taj_orig.jpg" />
        </imageobject>
        <caption>
          <para>Original image</para>
        </caption>
      </mediaobject>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="JPG"
            fileref="images/filters/examples/render/taj-lava.jpg" />
        </imageobject>
        <caption>
          <para><quote>Lava</quote> applied (on a selection)</para>
        </caption>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>

    <para>
       The lava filter generates a lava-like effect on the current layer or
       selection.
    </para>
  </sect3>


  <sect3>
    <title>Activating the Filter</title>
    <para>
      This filter is found in the main menu under
      <menuchoice>
        <guimenu>Filters</guimenu>
        <guisubmenu>Render</guisubmenu>
        <guimenuitem>Lavaâ€¦</guimenuitem>
      </menuchoice>.
    </para>
  </sect3>

  <sect3>
    <title>Options</title>
    <para>
      <!--
        Describe how the filter options are organized in general.
        This part is optional, but helps if the filter options dialog is a bit
        more complex e.g. has some tabs etc.
       -->
    </para>
    <figure>
      <title><quote>Lava</quote> options</title>
      <mediaobject>
        <imageobject>
          <imagedata format="PNG"
            fileref="images/filters/render/lava.png" />
        </imageobject>
      </mediaobject>
    </figure>

    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Seed</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            The lava generator uses randomization to generate the rendered lava.
            <guilabel>Seed</guilabel> determines the starting value. Using the
            same seed generates the same lava pattern.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Size</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This determines the size of the lava flows. Higher values create
            straighter lines.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Roughness</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This controls the straightness and amount of turns of the lava lines.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Gradient</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            This allows you to set the
            <link linkend="gimp-concepts-gradients">gradient</link> to be used
            for the lava effect.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Keep selection</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            If a selection is present, the lava filter only creates lava inside
            the selection. This setting decides whether to keep the selection
            after the filter has finished.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Separate layer</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            When enabled the lava is created on a new layer; when disabled the
            lava is added to the current layer.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term>Use current gradient</term>
        <listitem>
          <para>
            When enabled this selects the current gradient as set in the
            <link linkend="gimp-tool-gradient">Gradient tool</link>.
          </para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect3>
</sect2>
